		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31923645">I tweeted this nonsense after finishing the movie about a month ago <div class="spoiler"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.nextSibling.nextSibling.style.display='block';this.style.display='none';" value="Show spoiler"> <span class="spoiler_content" style="display:none"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.parentNode.style.display='none';this.parentNode.parentNode.childNodes[0].style.display='block';" value="Hide spoiler"><br>I&rsquo;m still not sure I understand how I feel about the Madoka movie. Simply as a visual /thing/, it&rsquo;s fucking incredible. Like, absolutely a joy to watch start to finish. Some of the fight scenes are just incredible, and the dreamy environments are just really cool and imaginative. In a substance/style marriage sense, I do think the visuals go further than necessary to the point where they supersede the story in places, in sort of a showboat-y, slightly disruptive way. Focus taken away from more subdued interpersonal moments in favor of kaleidoscopic spectacle. Stuff like that. <br />
<br />
A bit of a tangent here, but: in my opinion, style alone can carry something if that&rsquo;s what it sets out to do. Stuff like Redline or Dead Leaves, for example, thrive on their style to the point where it becomes their main selling point. It makes them an absolute blast to watch, and there&rsquo;s value in that. Fun is cool. BUT, those works also do not attempt to have a story, at least not to an egregious extent. <br />
<br />
Madoka 3 does though. And that&rsquo;s maybe my biggest problem with it, which sounds dumb conceptually. I suppose my bigger problem with the film is that it is ALL premise. Right up to the credits, the majority of the dialogue is explicating some detail of the premise. The ending of the series felt pretty conclusive, with all loose threads tied up&hellip; and this just feels like they spend most of the runtime trying to convolute a situation where it isn&rsquo;t conclusive anymore. I mean, the central idea of the film brings with it a lot weird issues when connected to the main series, and the rest is spent smoothing those out. Which, to be fair, it does. I just never really felt the premise was allowed to breath beyond that. Or something. <br />
<br />
Not that the story was completely void of neat ideas; there were a great number of them. I actually think the movie was pretty good overall. Worth a watch, at least. I&rsquo;m honestly still sorting out my thoughts on it though. This is just a rough idea of how I feel right after watching it. If nothing else, the visuals alone make it worth watching.<br />
<br />
Also&hellip; man, did you see those henshins? wow. they were so cool! and i was like &ldquo;wow&rdquo; <br />
<br />
and also &ldquo;those are so cool!&rdquo;<!--spoiler--></span></div><br />
<br />
And really, I'm still not sure how I feel about it. That's kinda why I wanted to nominate it, really. So yes, please elaborate, you two.<br />
<br />
Oh, and that cake scene was like the best part of the movie.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig"><div style="text-align: right;"><!--link--><a href="http://drillmilkyholmes.wordpress.com/" rel="nofollow"><img src="http://i.imgur.com/7ALjX4f.png" /></a></div></td>
