		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31935663">Typing this on my little sister's iPhone so sorry if I am not sufficiently verbose because it is frustrating writing on this thing.<br />
<br />
As others have pointed out, the greatest thin about this movie is it's visuals. It looks amazing, from the first frame to the last, never yielding in an effort to please the eyes in a grand, satisfying way. The greatest strength here compared to the television series is that the Gekidan Inu Curry designs and animation concepts are allowed to exist outside of the constraints that the original series called &quot;labyrinths&quot;. They are dutifully and beautifully integrated into the city or buildings or chalk-rainbow worlds that are distinctly not Gekidan Inu Curry. Because of this, all of the visual strengths Madoka as a franchise boasts are able to live and breathe freely, mingling and interacting and otherwise existing together in a two hour long grandiose spectacle. Really, the visuals alone are so good that I wouldn't have much minded if it had no dialogue ever.<br />
<br />
There is though, which might have been the thing keeping me from loving this film as much as I do. But I find that the complaints voiced frequently (including here in this discussion) about the plot being simply laid on the table, the story being all-concept with every word spoken furthering the explanation and reasoning for the ideas that the film's plot is built upon - these things are what make the movie work. There is not any nuanced character interaction or hidden details in the story for you as a viewer to be concerned with, because those things would be distracting, pulling you away from the main event that is the lovely and constant stream of creativity and animation.<br />
<br />
Because there are only two major story elements introduced in this movie, and I've never really seen Kyubey's motivation or reasoning questioned, I am going to address Homura's, and why her decision is actually a good addition to the Madoka story. Homura's obsessive, powerful love didn't come with real consequences in the end of the television series. She suffered, over a long time, but in the end her feelings created the Madoka we see at the end of the show; she would not have been so powerful, would not have accumulated all of those metaphorical threads of fate that increased her potential if Homura had not gone through that process so many times. In this way, Homura is really the hero who gave Madoka that chance to save the magical girls and create the law of cycles. Rebellion, then, uses its time to address the unhealthy obsession that Homura harbored which allowed her to persist for so long. Love can be, after all, toxic, selfish, and harmful, and that is exactly the kind of love Homura held for Madoka. Those feelings are not only negative and unhealthy but also incredibly strong, so it is hard to believe Homura wouldn't take her chance to capitalize on a situation like the one she is given at the end of this movie, to take Madoka for herself without even being aware of how cruel it is to the person she thinks she loves and how selfish it is of her.</div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig">&quot;My tables-meet it is I set it down<br />
That one may smile, and smile, and be a villain.&quot;</div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
